 Here is the code for a C++ program that demonstrates dynamic memory allocation and deallocation using pointers. The class 'ArrayHandler' has methods to allocate an array dynamically, fill it with numbers, and then deallocate the memory properly. 

```cpp
// File Name: ArrayHandler.h

#ifndef ARRAYHANDLER_H
#define ARRAYHANDLER_H

class ArrayHandler {
    int *array;
    int capacity;
public:
    // Constructor to allocate memory for the array and initialize it with zeroes
    ArrayHandler(int capacity);

    // Accessor functions for the array
    int& at(int index) const;
    int* begin() { return array; }
    int* end() { return array + capacity; }

    // Function to dynamically allocate memory and initialize an array with given size
    void allocate();

    // Function to fill the array with numbers from 0 to capacity - 1
    void fill(int value);

    // Function to deallocate the dynamic memory allocated for the array
    void deallocate();
};
```

Now, let's write the implementation file:

```cpp
// File Name: ArrayHandler.cpp

#include "ArrayHandler.h"

using namespace std;

void ArrayHandler::allocate() {
  array = new int[capacity];
}

void ArrayHandler::fill(int value) {
  for (int i = 0; i < capacity; i++) {
    array[i] = value;
  }
}

void ArrayHandler::deallocate() {
  delete[] array;
  array = nullptr;
}
```

 Here is a simple Kotlin function for an Android app that takes a user's input string, reverses it, and displays a Toast message with the reversed string. The code is commented to explain the functionality of each line.

```kotlin
fun reverseString(input: String): String {
    // Define an empty string variable to store the reversed input
    var reversedInput = ""

    // Loop through each character in the input string and add it to the reversed input 
    for (i in input.indices) {
        if (i != input.length - 1) {   // Excluding the last character since we don't need to reverse it
            reversedInput += input[input.length - i - 1]
        } else {                     // Reversing the last character
            reversedInput += input[i]
        }
    }

    // Return the reversed string
    return reversedInput
}
```

