#include <iostream>
#include <cstdlib>
using namespace std;

class ArrayHandler {
public:
    // Constructor to allocate the array dynamically
    ArrayHandler(int size) {
        arr = new int[size];
    }

    // Method to fill the array with numbers
    void fillArray() {
        for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
            arr[i] = i + 1;
        }
    }

    // Destructor to deallocate the memory properly
    ~ArrayHandler() {
        delete[] arr;
    }

private:
    int* arr;
};

int main() {
    ArrayHandler ah(10);
    ah.fillArray();
    return 0;
}
```
In this program, the `ArrayHandler` class has a constructor that allocates an array of integers dynamically using the `new` operator. The `fillArray()` method is used to fill the array with numbers. The destructor is used to deallocate the memory properly when the object goes out of scope.

In the `main()` function, we create an instance of the `ArrayHandler` class and call the `fillArray()` method to fill the array with numbers. When the program terminates, the destructor is called automatically, which deallocates the memory allocated by the constructor.

Note that in C++, it's generally recommended to use smart pointers instead of raw pointers for dynamic memory allocation. Smart pointers provide additional safety and convenience features, such as automatic memory management and exception safety.

