Here are some steps you can take to fix the issue:

1. Check your code for any references to objects that might be null. Look for instances where you might have forgotten to assign a value to a variable or where you're referencing an object after it has been released or destroyed.

2. If you've declared an object but haven't assigned it a value, make sure you do so before attempting to use it. For example:
   ```
   // Declare the object but don't assign a value yet.
   String name;

   // This line will throw a NullPointerException since 'name' is not initialized.
   System.out.println(name);

   // Assign a value to the object before using it.
   name = "John";
   ```

3. If you believe that an object may have been released or destroyed, ensure that you are not attempting to access its methods after it has been freed. For example:
   ```
   // This will throw a NullPointerException since 'obj' is no longer valid.
   obj.doSomething();

   // Use a conditional statement to check if the object is null before accessing it.
   if (obj != null) {
       obj.doSomething();
   }
   ```

4. If you still receive a 'NullPointerException', consider using a debugger to step through your code and determine exactly where the error is occurring.

