Quicksort is a divide-and-conquer sorting algorithm. The basic idea of this algorithm is to partition the array around a pivot element such that elements less than the pivot go to its left, while those greater go to its right. 

Here's how it works in steps:
1) Select an element from the array and assign it as a 'pivot'. This can be any element; we will choose the last one for simplicity.
2) Partition the elements based on whether they are less than or greater than pivot, putting them to either side of the pivot (in our case, right). 
3) Recursively apply these steps to both halves of partitioned array until it becomes a simple sorting problem for single-element arrays.

Pseudocode:
```
procedure quicksort(array, left, right) is
    if left < right then
        {
            pivotIndex <- partition(array, left, right);
            quicksort(array, left, pivotIndex - 1);
            quicksort(array, pivotIndex + 1, right);
        }
procedure partition(array, left, right) is
    {
        choose a pivot (for simplicity, we always choose the last element of array);
        i <- left - 1;
        for j <- left to right -  do
            if array[j] < pivot then
                {
                    i++;
                    swap array[i] and array[j];
                }
        swap array[i + 1] and array[right]); //swap the pivot element with the element at position i+1
        return i + 1;  //return pivot's final sorted index
    }
```
Python implementation:

```python
def quicksort(arr, low, high):
    if low < high:

        # pi is partitioning index, arr[p] is now at right place
        pi = partition(arr,low,high)

        # Separately sort elements before and after partition and return
        quicksort(arr, low, pi-1)
        quicksort(arr, pi+1, high)

def partition(arr,low,high):
    i = ( low-1 )         # index of smaller element
    pivot = arr[high]     # pivot

    for j in range(low , high):

        # If current element is smaller than or equal to pivot
        if   arr[j] <= pivot:
            i += 1
            arr[i],arr[j] = arr[j],arr[i]

    arr[i+1],arr[high] = arr[high],arr[i+1]
    return ( i+1 )

# Test the program
arr = [10, 7, 8, 9, 1, 5]
n = len(arr)
quicksort(arr,0,n-1)
print("Sorted array is:")
for i in range(n):
    print ("%d" % arr[i])
```
This will output the sorted array. The complexity of quicksort in the average case is O(N log N), but it can degrade to O(N^2) if you choose a poor pivot (like always picking the smallest or largest element). However, this worst-case scenario doesn't happen very often in practice.

