A NullPointerException is one of the most common exceptions thrown by a Java program. It indicates that you're attempting to use an object reference before assigning it a value, or while it doesn't refer to any object at all (or "null"). You should never get this exception. If you do, it's because either you don't have enough control over the code to avoid the problem, or there's a bug in your program that needs to be fixed.

The most common cause of a NullPointerException is using an uninitialized object reference as if it points to a valid object. If you call a method on an uninitialized reference, the virtual machine will throw a NullPointerException. Here's some example code:

```

Foo foo = null;  // no initialization!
if (foo != null)
    foo.bar();
else {
    Foo anotherFoo = new Foo();
    foo.baz();
}
```

This is a bad code snippet for many reasons, but the most obvious one is that if you call `foo.bar()`, you'll get a NullPointerException because `foo` has not been initialized to refer to an object. The fix? Don't use `foo` until it is initialized.

Another common cause of this exception is when you pass in a parameter whose value might be null, and then try to invoke a method on that parameter:

```

Foo foo = ...;  // initialized!
if (bar != null) {
    if (bar.isBar()) {
        bar.baz(); // no exception here because bar is not null
    } else {
        bar.quux(); // NullPointerException because bar == null
    }
}
```

The fix? Again, don't use `bar` until it has been initialized to refer to an object (or don't do anything with it that could throw a NullPointerException if `bar == null`). If you can't avoid the problem, make sure your code is resilient to null values.

In either of these situations, you need to change your code so that you are less likely to access an object reference when it has not been initialized or may be null.

There are other ways to cause a NullPointerException. For instance, if you call `null.bar()`, you will get one (or at least I hope you do). If you try to use any object's methods before initializing the object reference, you will also get an exception.

I've only shown code snippets in this article; it's important to note that NullPointerExceptions are most common in larger programs, where it can be difficult to locate where the offending statement is. If you get a NullPointerException from your program, try to isolate and simplify the code until you find the problem statement or method call.

