Here is an example of a C++ program that demonstrates dynamic memory allocation and deallocation using pointers:
```
#include <iostream>
#include <memory>

class ArrayHandler {
 public:
  // Constructor to allocate memory for the array
  ArrayHandler(int size) {
    // Use new operator to allocate memory for the array
    std::unique_ptr<int, decltype(std::free)*> p(new int[size]);
    // Fill the array with numbers
    for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
      p[i] = i * 2;
    }
    // Set the pointer to the allocated memory
    array_ = p.get();
  }

  // Method to deallocate the memory
  ~ArrayHandler() {
    std::free(array_);
  }

  int* getArray() { return array_; }

 private:
  int* array_;
};

int main() {
  ArrayHandler handler(5);
  // Use the array
  for (int i = 0; i < 5; ++i) {
    std::cout << handler.getArray()[i] << " ";
  }
  std::cout << std::endl;

  // Deallocate the memory
  handler.~ArrayHandler();

  return 0;
}
```
In this program, we have created a class named `ArrayHandler` that has a constructor that takes an integer parameter `size`. The constructor uses the `new` operator to allocate memory for an array of `int`s and then fills the array with numbers. The `~ArrayHandler()` method is used to deallocate the memory when the object goes out of scope.

The `getArray()` method returns a pointer to the allocated memory, which can be used to access the array elements. In the `main()` function, we create an instance of `ArrayHandler` and use the `getArray()` method to access the array elements. We then call the `~ArrayHandler()` method to deallocate the memory when we are done with it.

Note that this program uses C++11 features such as `std::unique_ptr` and `std::free` for dynamic memory allocation and deallocation. Also, the `getArray()` method returns a pointer to the allocated memory, which is not a safe practice in modern C++. Instead, we should use a reference or a copy of the array to avoid data race conditions.

